description:
Morgan Housel, is a tariff expert, investor and bestselling author of The Psychology of Money and Same As Ever, is one of the worlds top experts on financial psychology, economic collapse warnings, and building true financial freedom. His life-changing insights have transformed how millions approach money, investing, and wealth-building.

00:00 Intro
02:00 Timeless Lessons of Greed, Wealth, and Happiness
04:40 The Current Tariff Situation in 2025
06:54 What Are Tariffs?
11:41 Trump's True Reason for the Tariffs
18:13 Why Is China the Factory of the World?
20:25 China Stopped Being a Cheap Labour Country
22:54 What's the Impact of the Tariffs?
24:57 America's Trust
26:32 Are We Heading for a Recession?
29:20 The Importance of Backups During a Recession
30:38 How to Be Financially Free in 2025
35:49 The Evolutionary Desire to Show Off  Status
40:32 Salary Differences
42:58 We Have a Distorted View of Financial Wealth
44:18 Advice for the Economic Crisis
45:44 How Much Money Do You Need Saved?
46:45 The Impact of AI in Our Wealth Building
56:11 The Skills You'll Need in the AI Era
57:45 How to Have a Money Mindset
01:00:35 Why People Get Stuck in Crypto Scams
01:03:13 Women vs. Men: Who's Better at Saving and Taking Risks?
01:05:54 Crypto
01:07:02 What History Tells Us About New Technologies, Wealth, and Failure
01:08:30 Could the Crypto Security System Be Broken?
01:10:00 The Strategies Wealthy People Use
01:11:34 Intelligence vs. Endurance
01:13:07 Why Is Perseverance Key?
01:14:51 The Best Way to Have a Big Investment Return
01:16:40 The Power of Compounding in Your Savings
01:21:46 How Money and Psychology Are Linked
01:26:42 You Need to Change Your View on Savings
01:30:50 Biggest Regrets of People on Their Deathbeds
01:37:00 The Most Asked Questions About Finances
01:40:56 Where Are Your Investments Allocated?
01:41:43 Vanguard Index Fund
01:49:33 Where to Invest Spare Cash?
01:56:04 The Dangers of Retiring
02:03:10 How to Live a Happy Life

comments.text:
Thank you Mr Housel. I' living frugally, spending time with my autistic kid, cats and spouse who is half-deaf. I gave up career, big city life, almost all "friends" and I'm much happier than before. Every time I meet someone, they ask "are you back at work yet?" and I'm a bit shy, saying "no and I don't plan to in the near future". I'm growing veggies, having chickens, go camping for vacations. My kid is happy and healthy, he grows to be an exceptional human being. 
Expectations for a "success" is huge in modern society, but different from what a human needs.
My kid needs a lot of peace, quiet and nature. We visit cities, but live in rural area, in a small house with big garden. Don't have debt anymore and we can feed ourselves.

comments.text:
This is propaganda disguised as financial advice and a philosophy of "freedom within" which couldnt be farther from the truth. 
The Peter Thiel reference is particularly egregious considering he and his libertarian tech bros are systematically tearing apart our institutions, by explicit design, and gutting programs that help many that are already living a frugal lifestyle. 
Morgan has been pushing the wealth inequality is just perception bs for years now. How clever to fool so many into believing they can just change their state of mind and settle for less of everything while the wealthy build more wealth at our expense. We will literally own nothing and rent everything from our masters who apparently arent really all that happy. 
The grandma story is a complete farce. I guess grandmas rent and deposits never go up, she never has to service or replace her car, the increased cost of groceries, utilities and just about everything else doesnt effect her budget not to mention she never needs medical attention or medication. Thats one magical grandma life. We should all while the hours away in the garden for 1700 a month!
I would love to see Steven bring Theil on the show to discuss Network states, Praxis, his admiration of Curtis Yarvin and their plan to smash current governments and replace them with privately owned "mini-countries" where the wealthy rule like kings.
